The first time I made this I went to four grocery stores before I gave up trying to find rhubarb (including the frozen stuff). I substituted peaches, thinking they might add a bit of tang without getting too sweet. It was AWESOME. This year, I didn't even look for rhubarb.

Rating: 4
An enormous hit, two years in a row for Pesach. I used frozen rhubarb, which was easier and worked great.

Rating: 4
I made this to rave reviews, amongst those celebrating Passover and those not. I did reduce cooking time to 30 minutes and it was not runny and the crisp was pretty brown. In response to those that thought it too sweet, it's probably due to reducing the rhubarb - with all the sour in the rhubarb it needs the berries and the sugar to cut it. Tastes EXCELLENT cold!

Rating: 4
This was a big hit at our Seders this year. I made it with just strawberries, as I am not a big rhubarb fan. The mixture was a bit too sweet for me, but everyone else thought it was perfect. Next time I may try using less sugar. Either way, I will definitely make it again. For me, cooking 40 minutes was perfect. Two bonuses -- very easy to make and did not taste like a Passover dish.

Rating: 3
The recipe is easy and delicious but the temperature was way too high for baking the crisp - within 1/2 hour, the crumbs were beginning to singe. I would lower the temperature to 375 and bake until the crumbs are golden.

Rating: 4
The compote was fantastic, but if you cannot find or do not want to purchase Matzo or potato starch for just this dish, Martha Stewart's streusel topping works great.

